TY  - JOUR
AB  - This paper links the "coordination failure" and "menu cost" approaches to the microeconomic foundations of Keynesian macroeconomics. If a firm's desired price is increasing in others' prices, then the gain from price adjustment after a nominal shock is greater if others adjust. This "strategic complementarity" leads to multiple equilibria in the degree of rigidity. Welfare may be much higher in the equilibria with less rigidity. Thus, nominal rigidity arises from a failure to coordinate price changes.
